The code that's executed is:
```vec3 L      = normalize(o_lightdir);
vec3 N      = normalize(o_normal);
vec3 light1 = blinnphong(N, o_camdir, L, color.rgb);
color       = vec4(light1, color.a) + 
    backlight * vec4(blinnphong(N, o_camdir, -L, color.rgb), color.a);```
with blinnphong being defined here:
<https://github.com/JuliaPlots/GLMakie.jl/blob/2717d812fdc66b283f63d5d97237e8d69e2c1f25/assets/shader/standard.frag#L69>

ambient etc (as attributes) should affect both. And now that I look at it I get why things get brighter. diffuse and specular only change the color once (because only one of `dot(N, +-L) &gt; 0`), but ambient is added in both cases.

So with `ambient = Vec3f0(0.5 * 0.55)` and `backlight = 1f0` you should end up with the same brightness as before

